    To implement this:

    1. Set up Firebase: 
      bash
      1. Go to console.firebase.google.com
2. Create New Project

    2. Security Rules for Firestore:
    javascript
    rules_version = '2';
service cloud.firestore {
  match /databases/{database}/documents {
    match /exams/{examId} {
      allow read: if request.auth != null && 
                 request.auth.token.email.matches(".*@yourdomain.edu");
      allow write: if request.auth != null && 
                  request.auth.token.email.matches(".*@yourdomain.edu");
    }
  }
}

    Benefits of this approach:

    1. Only school email addresses can access admin
    2. Passwords stored securely in Firestore
    3. Track who created each exam
    4. Real-time updates when exams are added/modified
    5. Free for your usage level
    6. No server maintenance needed

    Question. does the location for my database matter? I am in south Africa and the options don't include any African countries

    No, the database location doesn't significantly impact performance for your use case, especially since it's just handling authentication and storing exam metadata (not the actual PDFs).

    For South Africa, here are the best options:

    1. europe-west1 (Belgium) - Generally good latency for South Africa
    2. europe-west2 (London) - Also good connection to SA
    3. asia-south1 (Mumbai) - Can be a good alternative

    The latency difference between these locations will be negligible for your application since:

    1. Authentication happens once per session
    2. Exam data is lightweight (just metadata and passwords)
    3. The actual PDFs are served from Google Drive, not Firebase
    4. Firebase caches data effectively

    I recommend choosing europe-west1 (Belgium) because:

    1. Good connectivity to South Africa via undersea cables
    2. Stable and reliable infrastructure
    3. Compliant with most data protection regulations
    4. Often used as default for African users

    Would you like me to:

    1. Continue with setting up the database?
    2. Add some performance optimization for SA users?
    3. Show how to monitor the connection performance?

    Remember, you can always change the region later if needed, but it's unlikely you'll notice any performance issues with any of these locations given the lightweight nature of the data being transferred.
